@pde I've updated the PR to remove from correct place.

I don't understand how this will break `letsencrypt-auto` for a lot of people. Anyone who is already using it will have had `mod_ssl` installed automatically already if it was not originally. For new users I don't believe it would be unexpected to find out they have to install `mod_ssl` if using Apache.

For those automating platforms with already written scripts that aren't properly installing `mod_ssl` along with `httpd` packages - I guess it would affect those and I'm sure there's a way to prevent that. Possibly by only installing `mod_ssl` if actually using Let's Encrypt to manage Apache.

Further examination of all the other bootstrappers leads me to believe this is purely RPM specific behaviour. For all other platforms, including Debian, I can see no code in their bootstrappers that triggers `mod_ssl` to be installed.

I think `letsencrypt-auto` should only be installing dependencies for Let's Encrypt to run. It should not install dependencies for the web server to run as IMHO that's not its job. Especially in my case, installing those dependencies directly impacts the running configuration on the server due to the introduction of `/etc/httpd/conf.d/ssl.conf`.

@FelixSchwarz is correct - I am not using Let's Encrypt packages from EPEL or anywhere. I installed it via `git clone`. This is specifically an issue with the `letsencrypt-auto` script

